</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=targonis>Targonis</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 775<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/7/03 2:10 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Best Damage Dealing Class in the high end game?</span><hr size=1> To answer the original poster, you need to look back at how the class balance was, and how things played out for wizards in groups, not just raids....<br>
<br>
Pre-Kunark, at level 40(max level), ice comet was an awesome spell, dropping 1110 per cast.  When mobs only had 32k HP, this was a LOT of damage, haste items were NOT common, and were fairly rare.  This had HIGH level wizards kicking ass if they had ice comet.  Rend came in and helped those without it.<br>
<br>
Kunark came out, and suddenly haste items were EVERYWHERE.  Melee damage went way up on the whole since many haste items wern't set NO DROP.  Caster damage went up, but as a whole, melees got a bigger improvement from Kunark.  Note that since spells are level restricted, it made it possible to really twink a melee to boost their power, while you couldn't boost a wizard's power by simply passing down sunstrike, or even a draught of fire spell.<br>
<br>
Also, downtime for wizards became a more obvious thing, we'd nuke, but most of the time we were sitting low on mana and not being able to contribute compared to the hasted melees.  Buffs for melees increased their abilities a LOT as well.<br>
<br>
Velious, the anti-caster expansion.  ZERO boost in damage output from spells.  HP cap on mobs removed, melee items boosting damage output and armor improvements increased making melees a lot more effective on mobs.  A FEW items had an effect called Flowing Thoughts to finally improve our mana regen.  Note there were perhaps 5 to 8 of these in game pre-Luclin.  A few DD items were available, but few and far between, most with very very long cast times.  Wizard DPS compared to melees dropped into the toilet.<br>
<br>
Finally, Luclin, the caster balance expansion.  Generally few UPGRADES for melees compared to previous expansions, more flowing thoughts items added, and AA abilities.   AA abilities boosted our long-term damage output, as well as our short term.  Even without the two new spells that boosted wizard damage(Elnerick's Electrical Rending and Garrison's Supperior Sundering), the AA abilities were enough to make wizards contribute decently again, if we had enough AA points spent in the right abilities.   Eventually, Focus items were added that boosted our damage even more.  Also, innate crits also came in to give us a TINY damage increase overall.<br>
<br>
PoP has continued to extend the abilities of wizards fairly compared to melees.  Unlike previous expansions, casters and melees generally were upgraded evenly.  New spells for wizards and new weapons and armor for melees boosted performance for both types of classes.  Strangely, the class that's gotten shafted the most has been warriors, because their ability to taunt mobs has NOT kept pace with the hybrid classes.  If taunt wasn't an issue, warriors would be doing ok, but their job is to hold agro, and they've been screwed.  With the AA abilities, and new spells, wizards really can pump out damage VERY well.  Mana regen items, and spells such as KEI(Luclin era mana regen spell that enchanters get), have made wizards a VERY powerful class.<br>
<br>
I hope this helps answer the original question.<br>
 <p>Targonis Manastorm<br>
Level 65 Wizard<br>
The Nameless Server<br>
